<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-663-761  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 663 761.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEEE Network  Nov 1990 v4 n6 p61(9).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>An architecture for human-network interfaces. (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Sonnenwald, Diane H.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>There is an opportunity today to create a new human-networkinterface (HNI) for the public switched telephone network.andP;  TheHNI architecture must be reusable to provide a common basis fordesign and development to reduce life-cycle costs, usable bysupporting a range of services and supporting customization basedon end-user differences; logically unified to promote commonlearning and skills and reduce interference and negative transferbetween services, empirically verified so designs are created andevaluated by end users in their environments, and reliable.andP;  A newHNI architecture is proposed.andP;  It consists of five components:physical device translation, logical device translation, dialoguecontrol, abstract application translation, and specificapplication translation.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Telephone SystemsUser InterfaceNetworksSwitchingNetwork Architecture.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Today's POTS interface architecture model. (chart)Today's operations interface architecture model. (chart)Proposed HNI architecture model. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>